<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp4sec1rsa" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>RSA Encryption</title>

  <p>In this section, we will discuss the RSA encryption scheme, which is one of the most important applications of number theory to our day-to-day live and is one of the most widely used public-key cryptosystems.</p>

  <p>
    The big idea is we want to create a way for people to send us secret numbers in a way that only we can read them.  We will do this by creating a public key that anyone can use to encrypt a message, and a private key that only we can use to decrypt the message.
  </p>
  
<p>
  We first select two primes <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>, and let <m>n=pq</m>.  
</p>



  <definition xml:id="definition-semiprime">
    <title>Semiprime</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A <term>semiprime</term> is an integer that is the product of exactly two prime numbers.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<p>
  The security of our encryption scheme relies on the fact that it is easy to compute <m>n</m> given <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>, but it is "hard" to compute <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> given only <m>n</m>.  To be more precise, the best known algorithm for factoring a large semiprime (the <term>General Number Field Sieve</term>) runs in time that is subexponential time in the number of digits of the semiprime.  So if we select <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> to be large enough, then it will be infeasible for an attacker to factor <m>n</m> and recover <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>.  In practice, it is standard to select <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> to be large primes, so that <m>n</m> is a large semiprime.  
</p>

<sage>
<input>
p = 83
q = 97
print(p, q)
n = p*q
print(n)
</input>
<output>
83, 97
8051
</output>
</sage>

<p>
  For example, the RSA-2048 semiprime has 617 decimal digits!    
  
  <md>
    RSA-2048 = 
  </md>
  


  As of Spring 2026, it has not been factored and successfully factoring would give a prize of $200,000.  
</p>

<p>
  We then select a <term>public exponent</term> <m>e</m> such that <m>1 &lt; e &lt; \phi(n)</m> and <m>\gcd(e, \phi(n))=1</m>.  We then compute the <term>private exponent</term> <m>d</m> such that <m>ed \equiv 1 \pmod{\phi(n)}</m>.  The <term>public key</term> is the pair <m>(n,e)</m>, and our <term>private key</term> is <m>d</m>.
</p>

<sage>
<input>
e = 7
print(xgcd(e, euler_phi(n)))
d = xgcd(e, euler_phi(n))[1] % euler_phi(n)
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>



<p>
  We post our public key <m>(n,e)</m> on our website, and we keep our private key <m>(n,d)</m> secret.  If someone wants to send us a secret number <m>m</m> such that <m>0 \leq m &lt; n</m>, they compute the <term>ciphertext</term> <m>c \equiv m^e \pmod{n}</m>.  They publish the ciphertext on our website.  
</p>

<sage>
<input>
m = 42
c = pow(m, e, n)
print(c)
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-rsa_decryption">
  <title>RSA Decryption</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are distinct primes, <m>n=pq</m>, <m>e</m> and <m>d</m> are integers such that  <m>\gcd(e,\phi(n))=1</m> and <m>ed \equiv 1 \pmod{\phi(n)}</m>, and <m>m</m> is an integer with <m>0 &lt; m &lt; n</m>, then <m>m^{ed} \equiv m \pmod{n}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof. Let the definitions structure your proof. You may find  <xref ref="proposition-generalized_fermat_little_theorem"/>, <xref ref="proposition-phi_function_of_prime"/>, and <xref ref="definition-phi_function"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<p>
  We can then decrypt the ciphertext by computing <m>c^d \equiv m^{ed} \equiv m \pmod{n}</m>.
</p>

<sage>
<input>
print(pow(c, d, n))
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

</section>